## Melt 1: From Thick Description to Void Architecture

The thesis gains power by being positioned at the end of a recognizable lineage.

### The Lineage

| Era | Author | Contribution | Void Translation |
|-----|--------|--------------|------------------|
| 1973 | Geertz | Thick description: context as interpretive frame | Void = the frame; scene = thin content |
| 1983 | Schön | Reflection-in-action | Void enables reflection; scene overwhelms |
| 1987 | Suchman | Plans as resources, not determinants | Void = resource; scene = failed plan |
| 1987 | Latour | Inscription and immutable mobiles | Void exports (immutable); scene doesn't |
| 1988 | Haraway | Situated knowledges | Void makes position explicit |
| 1997 | Agre | Indexical vs deictic | Void = indexical; scene = deictic |
| 2001 | Dourish | Context as achievement | Void enables achievement; scene pre-specifies |
| 2025 | Karpathy | "Context engineering" | Practice-level naming of what we theorize |

### The Claim

> Context engineering is the emerging practice of curating what enters an LLM's 
> context window. The void management thesis provides the *theoretical mechanism* 
> that explains WHY certain context engineering strategies work (bounded possibility 
> spaces) and WHY others fail (unbounded accumulation).

### The Contribution

Predecessors: Geertz said context matters. Suchman said plans fail. Karpathy said engineer the context.

Thesis adds: HOW to engineer it (void architecture) and WHY planning fails (complexity exceeds coherence).
