## Melt 2: Theoretical Triangulation

The thesis is now grounded by FIVE independent theoretical traditions:

### Tradition 1: Complexity Theory
- Simon (1962): Near-decomposability
- Brooks (1987): Essential vs accidental complexity
- THESIS: Void enforces near-decomposability; scene accumulates accidental

### Tradition 2: Situated Action
- Suchman (1987): Plans as resources
- Agre (1997): Indexical vs deictic
- THESIS: Void = indexical (local); scene = deictic (global)

### Tradition 3: Cognitive Science
- Miller (1956), Cowan (2001): Bounded capacity
- Sweller (1988): Cognitive load theory
- THESIS: Scene exceeds capacity; void respects it

### Tradition 4: Human-Centered AI
- Horvitz (1999): Mixed-initiative
- Shneiderman (2022): HCAI framework
- THESIS: Void management implements HCAI (high control + high automation)

### Tradition 5: Infrastructure Studies
- Bowker & Star (1999): Infrastructural inversion
- Latour (2005): Black-boxing
- THESIS: Void makes infrastructure visible; scene black-boxes

### Triangulation Claim

> The thesis is not a speculative construct. It is the intersection of five 
> independently validated theoretical traditions. If ANY of the five traditions 
> is correct, the thesis gains support. All five converge on the same conclusion: 
> bounded structures scale; unbounded accumulation collapses.
</melt>

