<melt id="abstract" className="melt">
## Melt 4: Unified Extended Abstract

### TITLE
**Void Management: A Theoretical Framework for Context Engineering in LLM-Assisted Creative Systems**

### ABSTRACT (250 words)

Generative AI systems increasingly support iterative creative work, yet their 
collaboration patterns remain poorly theorized. We introduce *void management*, 
an architectural framework that distinguishes two paradigms: *scene management*, 
where LLMs construct cumulative content requiring full context to modify, and 
*void management*, where LLMs prepare bounded possibility spaces that users 
instantiate.

We ground this distinction in five theoretical traditions: complexity theory 
(Simon, Brooks), situated action (Suchman, Agre), cognitive science (Sweller, 
Cowan), human-centered AI (Shneiderman, Amershi), and infrastructure studies 
(Bowker, Star, Latour). We position void management within the emerging practice 
of *context engineering* (Karpathy, 2025), providing the theoretical mechanism 
that explains why certain context curation strategies succeed (bounded spaces) 
and others fail (unbounded accumulation).

Through 150+ hours of design research, we developed POML (Prompt Orchestration 
Markup Language), a 1,300+ line prompt library that embodies void management 
principles. We demonstrate the framework across 10 design interventions, from 
speculative fiction to ethics tools to privacy frameworks. Evidence includes 
failure-success pairs: TILTH (scene management) collapsed; Thousand-Tetrad 
(void management) scales.

The thesis is falsifiable: scene-managed systems sustaining >20 iterative 
modifications without coherence collapse would refute it. We contribute: (1) the 
void/scene distinction, (2) a mechanism explaining context degradation, (3) 
architectural principles for context-engineering practice, and (4) exportable 
void structures (POML, disc-data.json) as proof of concept.

---

### KEYWORDS
Context Engineering, Human-AI Collaboration, LLM, Prompt Engineering, 
Creative AI, Bounded Rationality, Situated Action, HCAI
</melt>

